b'' b'' b'[ -and many others mailed me. here is a reply to one of the letters. seems to' b'me that atheist do not like the doctrine of hell!]' b'' b"there's nothing like a preacher to put fear into an" b' ignorant man...' b'' b"if god hadn't created hell in the first place, there'd be no" b' no need to "die" and save us. isn\'t it also a bit paradoxical' b' to say "god died" when, in fact, no such thing is remotely' b' possible. can the infinite die?' b'' b'your using 20th century concepts to interprete 1st century writers. of course,' b'in your termonology, god could not "cease to exist." however, that is not what' b'death ever means in the scriptures. if you will study the word, you will see' b'that it signifies "separation." death is separation, not ceastation. this is' b'the reason for the agony of the cross. for the first time in eternity, one' b'member of the godhead was separated from the other two.' b'' b'i once met a young lady that was as beautiful as any model that ever lived.' b'she was as personable as any saint ever imagined. she was to become my' b'"girlfriend" for several years. however, having been drafted, we were' b'separated by distance. to me that was a form of death. later, she decided' b"that she couldn't wait for me to come home and bid me adue. that to me was" b'death. it was separation from that which had made me whole. death is' b'separation and eternal death is eternal separation from his fellowship, not' b'because he chose to send you into outer darkness, but because you chose to go' b'there.' b'' b' did you know that jesus talked more' b' about hell than he did about heaven!' b'' b'thank you for this info. what respect i had for the man now' b' has been diminished tenfold. i promise never again to' b' say how wise or loving this man was...' b'' b'when i rebelled against my earthly father, he spanked me. i found no wisdom in' b'that until i had grown older and especially until i had my own children. he' b'was trying to guide me away from hurt that would enter my life if i continued' b'on my suicidal course. he did it in love though i interpreted it as harsh and' b'unloving. if god warns of impending danger, that is love. if choose to let us' b'do as we please, and then at the end tell us the rules, that would be harsh.' b'you have a conscience, no matter how calused or fallen it is, that witnesses to' b'you that a thing is wrong and that there is cause for fear.' b'' b'being jesus was allegedly god, i doubt he could honestly feel' b' the pinpricks man dealt him...' b'' b'this may give light to the error of your understanding. one must have correct' b'knowledge in order to have correct faith. faith and knowledge are inseparable.' b'jesus most certainly felt the "pinpricks" of life. as the scripture say:' b'' b'heb. for we do not have a high priest who cannot sympathize with our' b'weaknesses, but one who has been tempted in all things as we are, yet without' b'sin.' b'' b'the kenosis passage of phil states that he gave up his godhead attributes' b'when he took upon himself humanity. it has been a favorite meditation of mine' b'to think about this. it was to be my phd thesis. "the consciousness of' b'christ." i have talked at length with a great many people about this' b'interesting study, including clh.' b'' b'it is my conclussion that as jesus, the 2nd member of the trinity, actually' b'suffered as we do. he became part of the human race and experienced it as we' b'do. he "grew in knowledge." he chose not to grasp his omniscience, but chose' b'to be taught. it is my understanding that he was "led of the spirit" to such' b'an extent that sometimes it is hard to distinquish between jesus the man and' b'jesus as god. but in jn where the adulterous women was thrown before him,' b'the tenses are quite clear in that the whole situation took him by surprise.' b'that is, he was not aware that this event was to take place in time. he was' b'living sequential history as you or i.' b'' b'maybe some other time